<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: COLOMBO; KEY VOTE IN COLOMBO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In Sri Lanka, the teardrop-shaped Indian Ocean island traumatized by 11 years 
of civil war, voters go to the polls today in crucial parliamentary elections 
following a bloody campaign. 
</P>
<P>
 There are no dependable opinion polls, but many observers believe the 
opposition socialist People's Alliance will oust the centrist United National 
Party, which has been in power for 17 years.If it wins, the People's Alliance 
has promised to hold talks with the rebels who have been fighting for an 
independent Tamil homeland in a war that has claimed more than 30,000 lives. 
More than 130,000 police and troops are being deployed at the polls to prevent 
further violence. 
</P>
<P>
 Whatever the makeup of Sri Lanka's new Parliament, President Dingiri Wijetunge 
will remain president until new elections for that office are held in November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
