<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE PRESS; MAKING WAVES OVER DISSIDENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 With trouble in the streets of Havana, visions of a repeat performance of the 
1980 Mariel boat lift, one of Fidel Castro's more unpopular exports, were 
raised on editorial pages around the world. 
</P>
<P>
 In radio and television broadcasts from the Cuban capital, Castro, now in his 
34th year as Cuba's president, warned that he might open the gates and let 
malcontents on his island set sail for Florida. The Clinton Administration 
responded by threatening to order a naval blockade of Cuba, keeping its people 
ashore and preventing Florida-based Cuban Americans from seeking to deliver 
them. 
</P>
<P>
 In the 1980 boat lift, about 125,000 Cubans fled to Florida in a motley 
flotilla. Some of them were prisoners or mental patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
