<HEADLINE>
<P>
GLENDALE / BURBANK FOCUS: GLENDALE; MOST RESIDENTS SAY DOWNTOWN IS A BORE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE RYFLE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 While 80% of Glendale residents consider life in their city "excellent," 
"good" or "very good," only a few say they find interesting things to do 
downtown in the evenings and on weekends. 
</P>
<P>
 Those are some of the results of a recent survey of 2,178 Glendale residents 
conducted by the city and Glendale Partners, a group of prominent business 
people. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite several new entertainment draws downtown, including live theater, 
coffeehouses and even a trendy nightclub, many people still consider Brand 
Boulevard a big bore. 
</P>
<P>
 Still, officials say they are pleased with the results of the survey, which 
asked residents for their opinion on the past and future of the downtown area. 
The responses will be incorporated into a forthcoming "strategic plan" that 
will be used as a blueprint for future growth. 
</P>
<P>
 "One of the things the survey showed us was that despite some significant 
negative changes in the economy, attitudes toward Glendale have remained pretty 
positive," said Glendale Mayor Eileen Givens. 
</P>
<P>
 According to the survey, about 41% of residents want to see the downtown 
continue to develop at its current pace, 38% want it to slow down and 21% want 
it to stop.  
</P>
<P>
 Also, 32% said there should be more parking downtown, 29% said more cinemas, 
entertainment venues and nightclubs are needed, 25% said more police are needed 
to keep the area safe, and 20% said the area needs to be kept cleaner. 
</P>
<P>
 Questionnaires were distributed at a series of "town hall" public meetings on 
the future of downtown Glendale, which began in February. 
</P>
<P>
 The survey is part of a $350,000 project by the Glendale Redevelopment Agency 
and the Glendale Partners to create a communitywide consensus on the direction 
for the future building in downtown Glendale. 
</P>
<P>
 The Glendale Partners, an elite business group, has kicked in $125,000 and 
hired Alex Cooper, a New York urban planner, to oversee the study. 
</P>
<P>
 The strategic plan will probably be presented to the City Council by 
September, Givens said. A public discussion of the plan will be held from 7 to 
9 p.m. Wednesday at the Nestle Building, 800 N. Brand Blvd. STEVE RYFLE 
</P>
</TEXT>
