<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMPAQ TO CUT PRICES ON PC LINES; COMPUTERS: THE MOVE COULD SET OFF A PRICE WAR 
DURING THE INDUSTRY'S PEAK BUYING SEASON. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Compaq Computer Corp., which earlier this year took over as the nation's 
largest personal computer company, announced sweeping price cuts Monday on a 
wide range of products, a move that may trigger a price war. 
</P>
<P>
 The price reductions coincided with the start of the strong computer buying 
season, which runs from September to December. 
</P>
<P>
 The Houston-based company slashed prices up to 22% for virtually its entire 
line of Deskpro XL, Deskpro XE and ProLinea personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
 It also lowered prices up to 17% on most of its Contura and Contura Aero 
products. 
</P>
<P>
 There was concern that Compaq might be fueling a price war in the PC business, 
with the reductions coming at a time when prices for some components have 
declined and inventories have risen. 
</P>
<P>
 "My gut feeling is that some vendors will react and some will not. It depends 
on their overall strategy," said John Carlo Bisone, Compaq's senior vice 
president of North American marketing. 
</P>
<P>
 "The main point of this action is to combine affordability with availability," 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
 At the same time, Compaq said it is meeting demand for most of its product 
lines, with the exception of some models of its notebook computers. 
</P>
<P>
 "In the past, customers sometimes could not find the Compaq desktop 
configurations or the quantities they really needed. Now that issue is, for the 
most part, solved -- and at a more affordable price," said Ross Cooley, 
Compaq's senior vice president for North America. 
</P>
<P>
 The company has had problems in the past few quarters meeting demand for its 
products. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are pretty much current across the product line," Bisone said, adding that 
the company's price cuts are "not a fire sale" but an effort to continue to 
gain market share in the PC industry. 
</P>
<P>
 On Monday, San Jose-based market researcher Dataquest Inc. said Compaq is 
again the biggest U.S. maker of personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
 Compaq stock closed up 25 cents at $35.125 Monday on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
</TEXT>
